      "asbval:target_claim_text": "SUPPA2 with role: Generates transcript isoform structures and local alternative splicing event definitions from GTF annotation via generateEvents subcommand",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T17:56:07.172547+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/isoform-structure-annotation/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Alternative splicing is related to a change in the relative abundance of transcript isoforms produced from the same gene... These methods generally involve the analysis of either transcript isoforms [4\u20137], clusters of splice junctions [8, 9], alternative splicing events [10, 11], or exonic regions [12]. Relative abundances of the splicing events or transcript isoforms are generally described in terms of a percentage or proportion spliced-in (PSI)... exon-cassette (SE; 48.71%) and alternative splice site (A5/A3; 37.71%) events are the most frequent events in humans compared to mutual exclusion (6.22%) or intron-retention (7.36%)",
      "asbval:note": "The paper discusses alternative splicing event types (exon skipping/cassette, alternative splice sites, intron retention, mutual exclusion) and PSI quantification. However, the paper's scope is differential splicing analysis across conditions, not the upstream task of generating event definitions from GTF. The paper assumes PSI values are already calculated and focuses on testing for significant differences. The card describes a preprocessing/annotation step; the paper describes a downstream analysis step.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13059-018-1417-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "isoform-structure-annotation",
